industry has managed the tough sell of live music in a marketplace in which virtually everything is available online. Teasing out digital media's courtship of "liveness" in the production and consumption of K-pop, Kim investigates the nuances of the affective mode in which human subjects interact with one another in the digital age. Observing performances online, in concert, and even through the use of holographic performers, Kim offers readers a step-by-step guide through the K-pop industry's variegated efforts to diversify media platforms as a way of reaching a wider global network of music consumers. In an era when digital technology inserts itself into nearly all social relationships, Kim reveals how "what is live" becomes a question of how we exist as increasingly mediated subjects, fragmented and isolated by technological wonders while also longing for a sense of belonging and being alive through an interactive mode of exchange we often call "live."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aConcertszKorea (South) 0aConcertszKorea (South). 0aMusic and technologyzKorea (South) 0aMusic and technologyzKorea (South). 0aPopular musicxPerformanceszKorea (South) 0aPopular musicxPerformanceszKorea (South). 0aPopular musiczKorea (South)xHistory and criticism. 4aK-pop. 4acreative economy. 4adigital media. 4aglobalization. 4aidol. 4aliveness. 4amedia convergence. 4amultimedia. 4asocial media. 4asoft power. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360600540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503606005423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503606005.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyt